text: Looks as though mine with be a rare dissenting voice. From the man who butchered "The Spirit" comes another exercise in sheer, masturbatory stylistics. There is no story; there is only attitude. There is no emotion; there is only green screen. Ain't it cool. Obviously a lot of people are looking forward to it; goody. I can't imagine wasting a penny on another Frank Miller pixelpalooza. Miller was an irreverent, inventive, iconoclastic talent back in the '80s and '90s. His stillborn "The Spirit" -- preceded by the execrable "Robocop II" -- showed him far past the limits of his abilities and insights. When pose and preen replace heart and story, a movie is doomed, no matter how striking its look is. Go enjoy, everybody. I hope it's better than the trailer would indicate. And I await the brickbats!

text: Saw it tonight. By the way, I'm no teenager...The first half is pretty much a gas...great visual fun. The segue from the titles into the film is really great, and that damn score is fabulous.And of course, plenty of Marv. Turns out James Brolin brings it. He's really perfect for this stuff. So, great kinetic sequences..so over the top you have to laugh...which means you're being entertained. Thought the last quarter of the film was a bit too talky. I find myself just turning away from all the head chopping scenes later in the film....you get burned out with that.Note the cameo of Stacey Keach is somebody who looks more like a giant toad than anything else....Oh, and there's a Tarentino preview for Hateful Eight, which only uses graphics, and really...the graphics are more Rodriguez than Tarentino.
